Year = {{1992}},
Volume = {{43}},
Number = {{4}},
Pages = {{597-619}},
Month = {{DEC}},
Abstract = {{Most studies of relations between soil properties fail to take account
   of their regionalized nature because of the lack of appropriate methods.
   This paper describes a geostatistical technique, factorial kriging
   analysis, that bridges the gap between classical multivariate analysis
   and a univariate geostatistical approach. The basic feature of the
   method is the fitting of a linear model of coregionalization, i.e. all
   experimental simple and cross-variograms are modelled with a linear
   combination of basic variogram functions. A particular variance
   covariance matrix, the coregionalization matrix, can then be associated
   with each spatial scale defined by the range of the basic variogram
   function. Each coregionalization matrix describes relationships between
   variables at given spatial scale. A principal component analysis of
   these matrices produces a set of components, the regionalized factors,
   that reflect the main features of the multivariate information for each
   spatial scale and whose scores are estimated by cokriging.
   The technique is described and illustrated with three case studies based
   on a simulated data set and soil survey data. The results are compared
   with those of the principal component analysis of the
   variance-covariance matrix and the variogram matrices.}},
